## 4. CRDT vs Operational Transform Analysis

### 4.1 Operational Transform (OT)

**Advantages:**
- Mature technology with proven implementations
- Smaller operation size (typically 10-50 bytes)
- Intuitive conflict resolution for text operations
- Lower memory overhead per document

**Disadvantages:**
- Requires central server for operation ordering
- Complex transformation functions prone to bugs
- Difficult to implement correctly for rich text
- Poor offline support and P2P scenarios

### 4.2 Conflict-Free Replicated Data Types (CRDT)

**Advantages:**
- Mathematically proven convergence properties
- No central coordination required
- Excellent offline support
- Simpler to implement correctly
- Natural support for P2P collaboration

**Disadvantages:**
- Larger memory footprint (2-10x vs OT)
- More complex garbage collection
- Larger operation sizes (50-200 bytes)
- Potential for unbounded growth without GC

### 4.3 Recommendation: Hybrid CRDT Approach

Given the scale requirements and complexity of maintaining OT correctness, we recommend a **CRDT-based solution** with the following optimizations:

```go
type CRDTDocument struct {
    ID          string
    Sequence    *RGASequence  // Replicated Growable Array
    Tombstones  *TombstoneGC  // Garbage collection for deletes
    Metadata    map[string]interface{}
    Version     uint64
    LastGC      time.Time
}

type Operation struct {
    Type        OpType        // Insert, Delete, Format
    Position    Position      // CRDT position identifier
    Content     string        // Text content
    Attributes  Attributes    // Formatting attributes
    ActorID     string        // User identifier
    Timestamp   time.Time     // Logical timestamp
    Signature   string        // Operation signature for integrity
}
```

## 5. Conflict Resolution Strategy

### 5.1 Text Operations

**Insert Conflicts:**
```
User A: Insert "Hello" at position [1,2,3]
User B: Insert "World" at position [1,2,3]

Resolution: Use actor ID as tiebreaker
Result: "HelloWorld" (if A < B lexicographically)
```

**Delete Conflicts:**
```
User A: Delete character at position [1,2,3]
User B: Insert "X" at position [1,2,3]

Resolution: Insert wins over delete (preserve user intent)
Result: Character remains with "X" inserted
```

### 5.2 Formatting Conflicts

```go
type AttributeConflictResolver struct {
    rules map[string]ConflictRule
}

func (r *AttributeConflictResolver) Resolve(attr1, attr2 Attribute) Attribute {
    switch {
    case attr1.Type == "bold" && attr2.Type == "italic":
        return MergeAttributes(attr1, attr2) // Combine formatting
    case attr1.Timestamp.After(attr2.Timestamp):
        return attr1 // Last-write-wins for same attribute type
    default:
        return attr2
    }
}
```

### 5.3 Structural Conflicts

For complex operations like list reordering or table modifications:

```go
type StructuralResolver struct {
    priority map[OpType]int
}

func (s *StructuralResolver) ResolveConflict(ops []Operation) []Operation {
    // Sort by priority, then timestamp, then actor ID
    sort.Slice(ops, func(i, j int) bool {
        if s.priority[ops[i].Type] != s.priority[ops[j].Type] {
            return s.priority[ops[i].Type] > s.priority[ops[j].Type]
        }
        if !ops[i].Timestamp.Equal(ops[j].Timestamp) {
            return ops[i].Timestamp.Before(ops[j].Timestamp)
        }
        return ops[i].ActorID < ops[j].ActorID
    })
    return ops
}
```

## 6. Persistence Layer Design

### 6.1 Multi-Tier Storage Architecture

```
┌─────────────────┐    ┌─────────────────┐    ┌─────────────────┐
│   Hot Storage   │    │  Warm Storage   │    │  Cold Storage   │
│   (Redis)       │    │  (PostgreSQL)   │    │  (S3/GCS)       │
│   Active docs   │    │  Recent docs    │    │  Archive docs   │
│   < 1 hour      │    │  < 30 days      │    │  > 30 days      │
└─────────────────┘    └─────────────────┘    └─────────────────┘
```

### 6.2 Database Schema

```sql
-- Document metadata and current state
CREATE TABLE documents (
    id UUID PRIMARY KEY,
    title VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL,
    owner_id UUID NOT NULL,
    created_at TIMESTAMP NOT NULL,
    updated_at TIMESTAMP NOT NULL,
    current_state JSONB NOT NULL,  -- Serialized CRDT state
    version_vector JSONB NOT NULL, -- Vector clock for causality
    size_bytes INTEGER NOT NULL,
    is_archived BOOLEAN DEFAULT FALSE,
    INDEX idx_owner_updated (owner_id, updated_at),
    INDEX idx_updated_archived (updated_at, is_archived)
);

-- Operation log for replay and conflict resolution
CREATE TABLE operations (
    id UUID PRIMARY KEY,
    document_id UUID NOT NULL REFERENCES documents(id),
    actor_id UUID NOT NULL,
    operation_type VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL,
    operation_data JSONB NOT NULL,
    logical_timestamp BIGINT NOT NULL,
    wall_clock_time TIMESTAMP NOT NULL,
    sequence_number BIGINT NOT NULL,
    INDEX idx_doc_sequence (document_id, sequence_number),
    INDEX idx_doc_timestamp (document_id, logical_timestamp)
);

-- Snapshots for fast document loading
CREATE TABLE document_snapshots (
    id UUID PRIMARY KEY,
    document_id UUID NOT NULL REFERENCES documents(id),
    snapshot_data BYTEA NOT NULL,  -- Compressed CRDT state
    operation_count BIGINT NOT NULL,
    created_at TIMESTAMP NOT NULL,
    INDEX idx_doc_created (document_id, created_at DESC)
);
```

### 6.3 Caching Strategy

```go
type CacheManager struct {
    l1Cache *sync.Map           // In-memory document cache
    l2Cache *redis.Client       // Redis distributed cache
    l3Store *postgres.DB        // Persistent storage
}

func (c *CacheManager) GetDocument(docID string) (*Document, error) {
    // L1: Check in-memory cache
    if doc, ok := c.l1Cache.Load(docID); ok {
        return doc.(*Document), nil
    }

    // L2: Check Redis cache
    if data, err := c.l2Cache.Get(docID).Bytes(); err == nil {
        doc := &Document{}
        if err := msgpack.Unmarshal(data, doc); err == nil {
            c.l1Cache.Store(docID, doc)
            return doc, nil
        }
    }

    // L3: Load from database
    doc, err := c.loadFromDatabase(docID)
    if err != nil {
        return nil, err
    }

    // Cache in L1 and L2
    c.l1Cache.Store(docID, doc)
    if data, err := msgpack.Marshal(doc); err == nil {
        c.l2Cache.Set(docID, data, time.Hour)
    }

    return doc, nil
}
```

## 7. Real-Time Communication

### 7.1 WebSocket Gateway

```javascript
class CollaborationGateway {
    constructor() {
        this.io = require('socket.io')(server, {
            transports: ['websocket'],
            pingTimeout: 60000,
            pingInterval: 25000
        });

        this.documentRooms = new Map();
        this.userSessions = new Map();
    }

    handleConnection(socket) {
        socket.on('join-document', async (data) => {
            const { documentId, userId, authToken } = data;

            // Authenticate user
            const user = await this.authenticateUser(authToken);
            if (!user) {
                socket.emit('error', { message: 'Authentication failed' });
                return;
            }

            // Join document room
            socket.join(`doc:${documentId}`);
            this.trackUserPresence(documentId, userId, socket.id);

            // Send current document state
            const document = await this.getDocument(documentId);
            socket.emit('document-state', document);

            // Notify other users
            socket.to(`doc:${documentId}`).emit('user-joined', {
                userId: user.id,
                name: user.name,
                cursor: null
            });
        });

        socket.on('operation', async (data) => {
            const { documentId, operation } = data;

            // Validate and apply operation
            const result = await this.applyOperation(documentId, operation);

            if (result.success) {
                // Broadcast to other users in the document
                socket.to(`doc:${documentId}`).emit('operation', {
                    operation: result.transformedOperation,
                    userId: operation.actorId
                });
            } else {
                socket.emit('operation-error', {
                    error: result.error,
                    operation: operation
                });
            }
        });
    }
}
```

### 7.2 Operation Broadcasting

```go
type OperationBroadcaster struct {
    kafka    *kafka.Producer
    redis    *redis.Client
    channels map[string]chan Operation
    mu       sync.RWMutex
}

func (b *OperationBroadcaster) BroadcastOperation(docID string, op Operation) error {
    // Immediate broadcast to connected users
    b.mu.RLock()
    if ch, exists := b.channels[docID]; exists {
        select {
        case ch <- op:
        default:
            // Channel full, log warning
            log.Warn("Operation channel full for document", docID)
        }
    }
    b.mu.RUnlock()

    // Persist to Kafka for durability and cross-region replication
    message := &kafka.Message{
        Topic: "document-operations",
        Key:   []byte(docID),
        Value: mustMarshal(op),
        Headers: []kafka.Header{
            {Key: "document_id", Value: []byte(docID)},
            {Key: "actor_id", Value: []byte(op.ActorID)},
        },
    }

    return b.kafka.Produce(message, nil)
}
```

